  1. Select those records where ‘first_name’ starts with “G” and city is ‘San Jose’

select *

SQL-assignment 3.docx¶

  1. Create an ‘Orders’ table which comprises of these columns – ‘order_id’, ‘order_date’, ‘amount’, ‘customer_id’
In [ ]:
create table Orders (order_id int, order_date date, amount int, customer_id int)
  1. Make an inner join on ‘Customer’ & ‘Order’ tables on the ‘customer_id’ column
In [ ]:
select * from Customer
inner join Orders
on Customer.customer_id = Orders.customer_id
  1. Make left and right joins on ‘Customer’ & ‘Order’ tables on the ‘customer_id’ column
In [ ]:
# Left join

select * from Customer
left join Orders
on Customer.customer_id = Orders.customer_id

# Right Join
           
select * from Customer
right join Orders
on Customer.customer_id = Orders.customer_id
  1. Update the ‘Orders’ table, set the amount to be 100 where ‘customer_id’ is 3
In [ ]:
update orders
set amount=100
where customer_id=3

SQL-assignment 4.docx¶

  1. Use the inbuilt functions and find the minimum, maximum and average amount from the orders table
In [ ]:
select Min(amount) as Minimum_Amount ,Max(amount)as Maximum_Amount,Avg(amount)as Average_Amount
from Orders
  1. Create a user-defined function, which will multiply the given number with 10
In [ ]:
CREATE FUNCTION multiply
(@a AS INT -- parameter a	   
)
RETURNS INT -- return type
AS
BEGIN
RETURN @a * 10 -- return statement
END;
  1. Use the case statement to check if 100 is less than 200, greater than 200 or equal to 200 and print the corresponding value
In [ ]:
select 
case when 100<200 then '100 is less than 200'
when 100>200 then '100 is greater than 200'
when 100=200 then '100 is equal to 200'
end as result

  1. Arrange the ‘Orders’ dataset in decreasing order of amount
In [ ]:
select * 
from orders 
order by amount desc
  1. Create a table with name ‘Employee_details1’ and comprising of these columns – ‘Emp_id’, ‘Emp_name’, ‘Emp_salary’. Create another table with name ‘Employee_details2’, which comprises of same columns as first table.
In [ ]:
create table Employee_details1
(Emp_id int,
Emp_name varchar(50),
Emp_salary int)


create table Employee_details2
(Emp_id int,
Emp_name varchar(50),
Emp_salary int)
  1. Apply the union operator on these two tables
In [ ]:
select emp_id from EMPLOYEE_DETAILS1
union
select emp_id from EMPLOYEE_DETAILS2
  1. Apply the intersect operator on these two tables
In [ ]:
select emp_id from EMPLOYEE_DETAILS1
intersect	
select emp_id from EMPLOYEE_DETAILS2
  1. Apply the except operator on these two tables
In [ ]:
select a.emp_id,a.emp_name 
from EMPLOYEE_DETAILS1 a 
inner join EMPLOYEE_DETAILS2 b 
on a.emp_id=b.emp_id

except		
   	
select b.emp_id,b.emp_name 
from EMPLOYEE_DETAILS2 a 
inner join EMPLOYEE_DETAILS1 b 
on a.emp_id=b.emp_id

  1. Display the “FIRST_NAME” from Employee table using the alias name as Employee_name.

  1. Display “LAST_NAME” from Employee table in upper case.

select upper(last_name) as last_name 
from employee
  1. Display unique values of DEPARTMENT from EMPLOYEE table.
In [ ]:

FROM employee;
  1. Display the first three characters of LAST_NAME from EMPLOYEE table.
In [ ]:

from employee
  1. Display the unique values of DEPARTMENT from EMPLOYEE table and prints its length.
In [ ]:

from employee
  1. Display the FIRST_NAME and LAST_NAME from EMPLOYEE table into a single column AS FULL_NAME. a space char should separate them.

from employee
  1. DISPLAY all EMPLOYEE details from the employee table order by FIRST_NAME Ascending.

  1. Display all EMPLOYEE details order by FIRST_NAME Ascending and DEPARTMENT Descending.

  1. DISPLAY details of the EMPLOYEES whose SALARY lies between 100000 and 500000.

  1. Display details of the employees who have joined in Feb-2020.

  1. Display employee names with salaries >= 50000 and <= 100000.
In [ ]:
select concat(first_name,' ',last_name) as name from employee

Where Salary BETWEEN 50000 AND 100000);
  1. DISPLAY details of the EMPLOYEES who are also Managers.
In [ ]:
select  e.first_name,e.last_name,e1.employee_title 
from employee e 
inner join employee_title e1 
on e.employee_id=e1.employee_ref_id 
where e1.employee='Manager'
  1. DISPLAY duplicate records having matching data in some fields of a table.
In [ ]:
WITH EmployeesCTE as  
(  
   SELECT*, ROW_NUMBER() over (PARTITION BY ID ORDER BY ID) as RowNumber  
   FROM Employee 
)  
Select *  FROM EmployeesCTE WHERE RowNumber>1
  1. Display only odd rows from a table.
In [ ]:
SELECT * FROM (
    SELECT *, Row_Number() OVER(ORDER BY employee_id) AS RowNumber FROM employee) t
WHERE t.RowNumber % 2 <> 0
  1. Clone a new table from EMPLOYEE table.
In [ ]:
CREATE TABLE new_table select * employee ;
INSERT INTO new_table SELECT * FROM employee;
  1. DISPLAY the TOP 2 highest salary from a table.
In [ ]:
WITH T AS
(
SELECT *,
   DENSE_RANK() OVER (ORDER BY salary  Desc) AS Rnk
FROM employee
)
SELECT salary FROM T  where Rnk in (1,2);
  1. DISPLAY the list of employees with the same salary.
In [ ]:
SELECT * FROM employee
WHERE salary IN     (SELECT salary      FROM employee e
WHERE employee.employee_id <> e.employee_id);
  1. Display the second highest salary from a table.
In [ ]:
select *from employee 
where salary=(select Max(salary) from employee);
  1. Display the first 50% records from a table.
In [ ]:
